Flames shot from Thassalin's jaws as the huge Thraki set a specific patch of forest ablaze and then circled overhead to detect movement. Strangely, the eerie screeching behind him ceased as he slowed down. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"What's this, Tenuk, you've already turned into a Thraki before!"
"If I fly myself, it's completely different from suddenly being lifted up by a huge pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel was obviously not in agreement with Nyssi's opinion. He looked less black than usual, and his claws had dug so deeply into Thassalin's back that the Thraki was bleeding. However, Thassalin apparently didn't mind this. Nevertheless, he had come to realize that he had frightened his new friends and landed on a clearing.
"I'm sorry, but I smelled something. I had to take care of that!"
"But did you have to drag us along too?" growled Tenuk as he climbed down from Thassalin's back and slid down the creature's tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We've abandoned our strong, great warrior! How on earth will he catch up with us again?"
" He'll think of something...," growled Nyssi. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not dumb."
"Sure, but can Retvik drive?"
Nyssi waggled her eyebrows and turned back to Tenuk. "Of course he can drive."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I haven't seen him drive a nice little car like Kayel's either. Besides, he only started taking the car for work because you always drive us. He only has his bicycle."
Loud laughter interrupted her. Thassalin suddenly found something utterly amusing, but no one knew what he was laughing about. It took a bit too long for Thassalin to calm down.
"I'm sorry, but I pictured your huge friend in armor on such a tiny little bicycle for Temthan kids. That was hilarious! I wish I had some kind of telepathy. A wonderful imagination! One I can't share!"
Kayel chuckled, as he could imagine what was going on in Thassalin's head. "Yes, that's right. But what did you smell, and why did you suddenly take off?"
Thassalin grunted, rose up, and vanished. When he returned shortly thereafter, he threw something lifeless at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare, gold-white dragon-like creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR SCREAMS. SMELL THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING DRIVES ME TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY CLOSE."
The powerful Thraki suddenly froze. Nyssi and Kayel froze as well and looked intently toward a gap in the clearing. Something large and black was staring at them and hissing. Whatever it was, it spread out two enormous pairs of wings and shot toward Thassalin, paying no heed to the three smaller beings between them. Kayel and Tenuk barely managed to take cover, but Nyssi was swept along and nearly thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and hurling him onto his back with his incredibly long, agile tail, before swinging himself into the air. The black, two-winged creature pursued them at high speed.
Kayel grumbled angrily as he took his rifle from his back and opened a bag containing a belt of ammunition. He slung the belt over his chest, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thrakian, and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey, Tenuk, could you transform into something that can fly?" asked Kayel.
"Do you want to follow her?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... One of them is a huge monster!"
"Yeah and? I'm standing here with a top-notch rifle in my hand and could shoot right away. But, well, how should I put it – I would have to be able to see it in order to hit it."
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to make more room. With a soft, pained grunt, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur turning into scales and his arms into wings. He quickly transformed into a normal, bright blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Get up."
Like an otherwise ordinary Thraki, Tenuk now had a neat, scaly shield running along his back. Fortunately, he had also grown a pair of spines on his back, allowing Kayel to hold on. It took a bit too long for Tenuk to achieve flight, but once airborne, he quickly oriented himself and tried to resume the pursuit.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they were not alone. A second dark creature shot up beneath them, and Tenuk could only barely avoid a collision.
"That's probably the other terrifying giant monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel furrowed his brow. He tried to shoot at the second beast, missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not respond. He was too preoccupied with focusing on the flight toward Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other beast was pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly turned around to keep an eye on the monster. The fact that it was following them was an advantage for Kayel, as it made it easier for him to aim and shoot. Two shots went through the upper wings of the creature. It let out a painful cry and fell back under the trees. Kayel wasn't sure whether it was still following them, but it certainly wouldn't be able to keep up with them.
A good distance ahead of them, Nyssi was desperately clinging on while Thassalin struggled and spat flames at the blackened monster. The creature was definitely injured. It seemed extremely angry, yet unwilling to back down. The fireballs didn't seem to have the desired effect. As Thassalin stretched, Nyssi seized the opportunity to draw her own weapon, an old shotgun. It wasn't exactly the first choice, but maybe the shot pellets would scare off the black beast.
